Creating my first Git repository was an important step in starting to work with version control and thinking more professionally about my code. 
I learned how a repository acts as a central place to store my project files, track changes, and keep a clean history of my work instead of just saving multiple file
versions manually. Initializing the repository, making my first commit, and pushing it to a remote platform made me more aware of the importance of clear commit 
messages and a logical project structure.


This process also showed me how useful Git can be for experimenting safely, since I can always go back to a previous version if something breaks.
